# Count Majority Subarrays

## 📌 Problem Statement

Given an integer array `nums` and an integer `target`, count the number of subarrays in which `target` is the **majority element**.

A value is considered a majority element in a subarray if:

```text
frequency(target) > length(subarray) / 2
```

Return the total number of such subarrays.

---

## 🧠 Approach

### Brute Force Enumeration

The solution checks every possible subarray and counts how many times `target` appears within it.

For each starting index:

1. Initialize the frequency of `target` to `0`.
2. Extend the subarray one element at a time.
3. Update the frequency whenever the current element equals `target`.
4. Compute the current subarray length.
5. If:

```text
frequency(target) > length / 2
```

then the subarray is valid and contributes to the answer.

---

### Why It Works

For every subarray:

```text
nums[i...j]
```

the algorithm maintains:

* `freq` = number of occurrences of `target`
* `len` = size of the subarray

A subarray is counted exactly when `target` appears more than half of its length.

Since all possible subarrays are examined, every valid majority subarray is counted.

---

## 💻 Code (C++)

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    long long countMajoritySubarrays(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.size();
        long long cnt = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int freq = 0;

            for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {
                if (nums[j] == target) {
                    freq++;
                }

                int len = j - i + 1;

                if (freq > len / 2) {
                    cnt++;
                }
            }
        }

        return cnt;
    }
};
```

---

## 🚀 Example

### Input

```text
nums = [1, 2, 2, 2, 3]
target = 2
```

### Valid Majority Subarrays

```text
[2]
[2,2]
[2,2,2]
[2,2,2,3]
[1,2,2]
[1,2,2,2]
[2]
[2,2]
[2,2,3]
[2]
...
```

Each counted subarray contains `2` more than half of the time.

### Output

```text
10
```

---

## ⏱️ Complexity Analysis

Let:

```text
n = nums.size()
```

### Time Complexity

The outer loop chooses the start index and the inner loop chooses the end index:

```text
O(n²)
```

### Space Complexity

Only a few variables are used:

```text
O(1)
```

